concept_explanation.intro:
**Method overloading**: defining multiple methods in the same class with the SAME NAME but DIFFERENT parameter signatures.

Simple example:

```java
public class Calculator {
    public static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }
}
```

Three methods, all named `add`. Java picks which one based on arguments:

```java
add(5, 3);          // calls add(int, int) → 8
add(2.5, 1.5);      // calls add(double, double) → 4.0
add(1, 2, 3);       // calls add(int, int, int) → 6
```

This is legal Java. It's also DRY — three methods, one concept, one name.

concept_explanation.varargs_brief_intro:
**Varargs** (variable-length arguments) is related to overloading. Lets you accept ANY number of arguments of the same type:

```java
public static int sum(int... numbers) {
    int total = 0;
    for (int n : numbers) {
        total += n;
    }
    return total;
}

// Call with any number of ints:
sum(1, 2);              // 3
sum(1, 2, 3, 4);        // 10
sum(5);                 // 5
sum();                  // 0
```

The `int...` syntax means 'zero or more int arguments.' Inside the method, `numbers` is treated like an array (we'll cover arrays in next module).

**When to use varargs**: when the number of arguments is genuinely unknown. Common in: printf-style formatting, building collections, logging.

**Caveats**:
- Only ONE varargs parameter per method (and must be LAST)
- Can clash with overloading — Java may struggle to pick between `sum(int, int)` and `sum(int...)` for `sum(1, 2)`. It will prefer the specific overload, but be careful.

We'll see more of varargs when we hit collections and Strings. For now, just know it exists.

concept_explanation.constructor_overloading_preview:
Constructors (covered in OOP module) are special methods for creating objects. They can be overloaded just like regular methods:

```java
public class User {
    // Constructor with all fields
    public User(String name, int age, String email) { ... }

    // Constructor with just name (defaults age and email)
    public User(String name) { ... }

    // Empty constructor
    public User() { ... }
}
```

This lets users create objects in different ways:

```java
User u1 = new User("Aisha", 28, "aisha@example.com");
User u2 = new User("Raj");
User u3 = new User();
```

We'll fully cover this in OOP. Mentioned now because constructor overloading is the most common form of overloading you'll see in real codebases.

step_by_step_solution.details:
Start with the most basic:

```java
public static void log(String message) {
    System.out.println("[INFO] " + message);
}
```

Usage: `log("Server started")` → prints `[INFO] Server started`

The default level is INFO. This is the convenience overload — for the common case.

Custom level support:

```java
public static void log(String level, String message) {
    System.out.println("[" + level + "] " + message);
}
```

Usage: `log("WARN", "Disk space low")` → prints `[WARN] Disk space low`

**Notice**: the parameter ORDER. We chose (level, message) — level first because it's the modifier. Java standard library convention: 'qualifier first, content last.'

For errors with codes:

```java
public static void log(String message, int errorCode) {
    System.out.println("[ERROR " + errorCode + "] " + message);
}
```

Usage: `log("Database timeout", 504)` → prints `[ERROR 504] Database timeout`

Notice this overload assumes errors. The presence of an `int errorCode` parameter signals 'this is an error log.' Reasonable shortcut.

The full version with everything:

```java
public static void log(String level, String message, int errorCode) {
    System.out.println("[" + level + " " + errorCode + "] " + message);
}
```

Usage: `log("FATAL", "System crash", 500)` → prints `[FATAL 500] System crash`

This is the most flexible. The other overloads are conveniences for common cases.

worked_example.final_code:
public class Logger {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        log("Server started");
        log("WARN", "Disk space low");
        log("Database timeout", 504);
        log("FATAL", "System crash", 500);
    }

    public static void log(String message) {
        System.out.println("[INFO] " + message);
    }

    public static void log(String level, String message) {
        System.out.println("[" + level + "] " + message);
    }

    public static void log(String message, int errorCode) {
        System.out.println("[ERROR " + errorCode + "] " + message);
    }

    public static void log(String level, String message, int errorCode) {
        System.out.println("[" + level + " " + errorCode + "] " + message);
    }
}

